  "prompt": "What is a ionic bond? What are some examples?",
  "response": "An ionic bond is a type of chemical bond formed by the electrostatic attraction between oppositely charged ions. Here's a detailed explanation:\n\nFormation of Ionic Bond:\n- Occurs between a metal and a non-metal\n- Involves the transfer of electrons from a metal atom to a non-metal atom\n- One atom becomes a positively charged cation\n- The other atom becomes a negatively charged anion\n- Strong electrostatic attraction holds the ions together\n\nExamples of Ionic Compounds:\n1. Sodium Chloride (NaCl)\n- Sodium (Na) loses an electron to Chlorine (Cl)\n- Na+ and Cl- ions form table salt\n\n2. Potassium Chloride (KCl)\n- Potassium loses an electron to Chlorine\n- Used in fertilizers and medical treatments\n\n3. Calcium Fluoride (CaF2)\n- Calcium loses two electrons to Fluorine\n- Found in tooth enamel and used in metallurgy\n\n4. Magnesium Oxide (MgO)\n- Magnesium loses two electrons to Oxygen\n- Used in manufacturing ceramics and refractory materials\n\nCharacteristics of Ionic Compounds:\n- High melting and boiling points\n- Conduct electricity when dissolved in water\n- Often form crystal lattice structures\n- Generally soluble in water",
